Certainly! Below is a complete HTML file that meets your requirements. It includes a vertical bar that can be repositioned, English filler text on the left, Hebrew text on the right, and input boxes below each text. The input boxes are set to match the text direction (LTR for English and RTL for Hebrew) and the appropriate glyphs.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Text Input with Vertical Divider</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .container {
            display: flex;
            align-items: stretch;
            width: 80%;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }
        .text-box {
            flex: 1;
            padding: 20px;
            position: relative;
        }
        .divider {
            width: 5px;
            background-color: #ccc;
            cursor: ew-resize;
        }
        .input-box {
            margin-top: 10px;
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        button {
            margin-top: 10px;
            padding: 10px 20px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <div class="text-box" id="english-box">
        <p style="direction: ltr;">Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua.</p>
        <input type="text" class="input-box" style="direction: ltr;" placeholder="Type in English...">
    </div>
    <div class="divider" id="divider"></div>
    <div class="text-box" id="hebrew-box">
        <p style="direction: rtl;">לורם איפסום דולור סיט אמט, קונסקטטור אדיפיסינג אלית. סד דו אאוסמוד טמפור אינצידידונט אוט לאבור ואט דולור מגנה אליקווה.</p>
        <input type="text" class="input-box" style="direction: rtl;" placeholder="כתוב בעברית...">
    </div>
</div>
<button id="submit-button">Submit</button>

<script>
    const divider = document.getElementById('divider');
    let isDragging = false;

    divider.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
        isDragging = true;
    });

    document.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
        if (isDragging) {
            const container = document.querySelector('.container');
            const containerRect = container.getBoundingClientRect();
            const newWidth = e.clientX - containerRect.left;
            if (newWidth > 50 && newWidth < containerRect.width - 50) {
                divider.style.left = newWidth + 'px';
                divider.style.position = 'absolute';
                divider.style.top = '0';
                divider.style.height = '100%';
                document.getElementById('english-box').style.width = newWidth + 'px';
                document.getElementById('hebrew-box').style.width = (containerRect.width - newWidth - divider.offsetWidth) + 'px';
            }
        }
    });

    document.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
        isDragging = false;
    });

    document.getElementById('submit-button').addEventListener('click', () => {
        const englishInput = document.querySelector('#english-box .input-box').value;
        const hebrewInput = document.querySelector('#hebrew-box .input-box').value;
        alert(`English Input: ${englishInput}\nHebrew Input: ${hebrewInput}`);
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The page is divided into two main sections (English and Hebrew) with a vertical divider in between.
- **CSS**: Basic styles are applied to layout the text boxes, divider, and input fields. The divider is styled to be draggable.
- **JavaScript**: The script allows the user to drag the divider to resize the text boxes. It also handles the submission of the input values, displaying them in an alert.

You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see it in action.
